# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1754-british-general-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] The **Eleventh Parliament of Great Britain** was the parliament of the Kingdom of Great Britain that sat from 31 May 1754 to 20 March 1761.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] It was assembled following the general elections held in April–May 1754.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] As with its predecessor, the Eleventh Parliament was an overwhelmingly Whig parliament.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] Traditional Whig–Tory party alignments had little meaning in the course of this parliament.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] Instead, political competition ran primarily between different Whig factions, such as the "Old Corps", Bedfordites, and Patriots.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] There were several changes of ministries in the course of the Eleventh Parliament.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] Thomas Pelham-Holles, Duke of Newcastle's "Old Corps" Whigs assembled the first ministry, but had to accommodate the rise of the Bedfordite faction in late 1755 with several cabinet posts.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] Newcastle's ministry fell in late 1756, during the parliamentary recess, and the third session began with a new Bedfordite–Patriot Whig coalition in control.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] However, King George II could not brook them and fired them before the end of that session, placing the government in the hands of an interim caretaker ministry.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] More satisfactory to the king, Newcastle returned to power in coalition with William Pitt before the beginning of the fourth session in late 1757.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] The Seven Years' War was fought for the duration of the Eleventh Parliament, and much of its legislation addressed the financing and conduct of the war.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] Surrey MP Arthur Onslow was Speaker of the House of Commons for the three prior parliaments, and had been re-elected to serve as speaker for the entire Eleventh Parliament.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] In the Cabinet, the Secretary of the South served as the Leader of the House of Commons.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] The "Old Corps" Whig Thomas Robinson held that office until late 1755, when the Bedfordite Henry Fox replaced him.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] In 1756, William Pitt took and held that position until the end of the parliament.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] The Prime Minister of Great Britain was Leader of the House of Lords during this parliament, namely Newcastle from 1756 to 1757, Devonshire briefly from 1756 to 1757, and Newcastle again from 1756 to 1761.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] The Eleventh Parliament went through eight sessions.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] Its first session opened on 31 May 1754 for only a few days for formalities, and passed no public act.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] Thereafter, parliamentary sessions usually opened in November and ran for around six months.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] They were in recess for the subsequent half of the year.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] Parliament was not immediately dissolved with the death of King George II (25 October 1760) but rather met for an additional eighth and final session that November, opened by the new King George III.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] The Eleventh Parliament was finally dissolved on 25 April 1761, and new elections called.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] By tradition, a parliament passes only one public "act" per session, albeit an act with multiple chapters.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] Legal statutes are cited by parliamentary session labelled by the regnal year in which that session sat: thus, for example, the British Museum Act 1753 (26 Geo 2 ch 22).
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] The regnal year of George II began on 11 June, and thus most parliamentary sessions do not overlap regnal years (and thereby do not need a double citation).
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] As this parliament was the first new parliament assembled after the calendar reform went into effect in 1752, there is no citation conflict between legal dates and common dates.
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] The session dates in the table below follow Cobbett's *Parliamentary History* (Cobbett 1813).
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] The legal titles of the sessions are as given in common compilations, such as the *Statutes at Large* (Pickering 1766).
[src:1754-british-general-election/11th-parliament-of-great-britain] For the specific acts of parliament passed in each session, see the list of acts of the Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] The **1708 British general election** was the first general election to be held after the Acts of Union had united the Parliaments of England and Scotland.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] The election saw the Whigs gain a majority in the House of Commons, and by November the Whig-dominated parliament had succeeded in pressuring the Queen into accepting the Whig Junto into government for the first time since the late 1690s.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] The Whigs only able to take partial control of the government, however, owing to the continued presence of the moderate Tory Godolphin in the cabinet (as Lord High Treasurer) and the opposition of the Queen.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] Contests were held in 95 of the 269 English and Welsh constituencies and 28 of the 45 Scottish constituencies.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] Following the election, Whig MP Lord Somers was appointed as Lord President of the Council.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] However, moderate Tory Lord Godolphin remained as Lord High Treasurer and the Godolphin–Marlborough ministry remained in place.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] In England, there were 513 MPs elected from 245 constituencies (203 boroughs, 40 counties, and 2 universities).
[src:1754-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] In Wales, there were 24 MPs from 24 constituencies.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] In Scotland, there were 45 MPs from 45 constituencies (30 counties and 15 burghs).
[src:1754-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] The first general election held since the Union took place between 30 April 1708 and 7 July 1708.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] At this period elections did not take place at the same time in every constituency.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] The returning officer in each county or borough fixed the precise date (see hustings for details of the conduct of the elections).
[src:1754-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] In England and Wales, the Whigs took 268 seats and the Tories took 225, with 20 unclassified.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] The 45 in Scotland could be classified as ministerial supporters.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The **1710 British general election** produced a landslide victory for the Tories.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The election came in the wake of the prosecution of Henry Sacheverell, which had led to the collapse of the previous government led by Godolphin and the Whig Junto.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] In November 1709 the clergyman Henry Sacheverell had delivered a sermon fiercely criticising the government's policy of toleration for Protestant dissenters and attacking the personal conduct of the ministers.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The government had Sacheverell impeached, and he was narrowly found guilty but received only a light sentence, making the government appear weak and vindictive.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The trial enraged a large section of the population, and riots in London led to attacks on dissenting places of worship and cries of "Church in Danger".
[src:1754-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The government's unpopularity was further increased by its enthusiasm for the war with France, as peace talks with the French king Louis XIV had broken down over the government's insistence that the Bourbons hand over the Spanish throne to the Habsburgs.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The Tories' policy of pursuing peace appealed to a country worn out by constant war.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] Queen Anne, disliking the Junto and sensing that the government could not survive long, gradually replaced it with a Tory ministry throughout the summer of 1710.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The election was bitterly contested in almost all the counties and "open" boroughs, even when a poll was not held.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] Contests occurred in 131 constituencies in England and Wales; approximately half of all English and Welsh constituencies.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The overwhelming Tory victory surprised few, and following the election most remaining Whigs resigned from office.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The new government was led by the moderate Tory Robert Harley who was unpopular among the more partisan Tories.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] Harley's ministry faced increasing pressure from the extremists whose position in Parliament had been enormously strengthened by the result.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] See 1796 British general election for details.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The constituencies used were the same throughout the existence of the Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The general election was held between 2 October 1710 and 16 November 1710.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The returning officer in each county or parliamentary borough fixed the precise date (see hustings for details of the conduct of the elections).
[src:1754-british-general-election/1713-british-general-election] The **1713 British general election** was held on 22 August 1713 to 12 November 1713, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of the Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1713-british-general-election] It produced further gains for the governing Tory party.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1713-british-general-election] The government remained popular with the electorate, however, having entered into peace negotiations ending the War of the Spanish Succession and later agreeing on the Treaty of Utrecht.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1713-british-general-election] The Tories consequently made further gains against the Whigs, making Harley's job even more difficult.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1713-british-general-election] Contests were held in 94 constituencies in England and Wales, some 35 per cent of the total, reflecting a decline in partisan tension and the Whigs' belief that they were unlikely to win anyway.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1713-british-general-election] The general election was held between 22 August 1713 and 12 November 1713.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] The **1715 British general election** was held on 22 January 1715 to 9 March 1715, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of the Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] It returned members to serve in the House of Commons of the 5th Parliament of Great Britain to be held, after the 1707 merger of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] In October 1714, soon after George I had arrived in London after ascending to the throne, he dismissed the Tory cabinet and replaced it with one almost entirely composed of Whigs, as they were responsible for securing his succession.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] The election of 1715 saw the Whigs win an overwhelming majority in the House of Commons, and afterwards virtually all Tories in central or local government were purged, leading to a period of Whig ascendancy lasting almost fifty years during which Tories were almost entirely excluded from office.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] The Whigs then moved to impeach Robert Harley, the former Tory first minister.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] After he was imprisoned in the Tower of London for two years, the case ultimately ended with his acquittal in 1717.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] The general election was held between 22 January 1715 and 9 March 1715.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] The **1722 British general election** elected members to serve in the House of Commons of the 6th Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] This was the fifth such election since the merger of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1707.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] Thanks to the Septennial Act 1715, which swept away the maximum three-year life of a parliament created by the Meeting of Parliament Act 1694, it followed seven years after the previous election, that of 1715.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] The election was fiercely fought, with contests taking place in more than half of the constituencies, which was unusual for the time.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] In the midst of the election, word came from France of a Jacobite plot aimed at an imminent coup d'état.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] Led by Francis Atterbury, Bishop of Rochester, Lord North and Grey, and other Tory opponents of Walpole, this was later known as the "Atterbury Plot".
[src:1754-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] Previously election results had broadly reflected the opinion of at least the minority of adult males who had the vote, although the system had always been subject to the influence of corruption and patronage.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] However, now that one-party government had been established, those influences could be used systematically to ensure the governing party's victory.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] This election set the pattern for much of the rest of the eighteenth century; as partisan feeling began to decline during the years of the Whig oligarchy, the rigging of elections became ever easier, so that British governments could almost always guarantee victory.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] The general election was held between 19 March 1722 and 9 May 1722.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] The **1727 British general election** returned members to serve in the House of Commons of the 7th Parliament of Great Britain to be summoned, after the merger of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1707.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] The election was triggered by the death of King George I; at the time, it was the convention to hold new elections following the succession of a new monarch.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] A group known as the Patriot Whigs, led by William Pulteney, who were disenchanted with Robert Walpole's government and believed he was betraying Whig principles, had been formed prior to the election.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] Bolingbroke and Pulteney had not expected the next election to occur until 1729, and were consequently caught unprepared.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] They failed to make any gains against the government party.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] The general election was held between 14 August 1727 and 17 October 1727.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] At this period, elections did not take place at the same time in every constituency.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1754-british-general-election] The **1754 British general election** returned members to serve in the House of Commons of the 11th Parliament of Great Britain to be summoned, after the merger of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1707.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1754-british-general-election] Owing to the extensive corruption and the Duke of Newcastle's personal influence in the pocket boroughs, the government was returned to office with a working majority.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1754-british-general-election] The old parties had disappeared almost completely by this stage; anyone with reasonable hopes of achieving office called himself a 'Whig', although the term had lost most of its original meaning.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1754-british-general-election] A small group of members of parliament still considered themselves Tories, but they were almost totally irrelevant to practical politics and entirely excluded from holding public office.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1754-british-general-election] The 106 seats they held at this election is the fewest they have ever held in history.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1754-british-general-election] In seats percentage terms, the Tories held 19% of the seats - the lowest proportion ever until surpassed by its successor Conservative Party's 18.62% (or 121 of 650 seats) won 270 years later.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1754-british-general-election] The resulting eleventh Parliament of Great Britain was convened on 31 May 1754 and sat through eight sessions until its dissolution on 20 April 1761.
[src:1754-british-general-election/1754-british-general-election] The general election was held between 13 April 1754 and 20 May 1754.
